True; A lawyer is allowed to draft and deliver documents that they know are fraudulent to assist their client if a client has:
a) Knowledge of the fraud; 
b) No reason to know that the document is fraudulent; 
c) An actual and reasonably trusting reliance on third-party assertions that are subject to difficulties that we once regularly called fraud or mistake. In every case, the representation of the client in the document's preparation, drafting, and delivering is deemed to be attendant to the legal or ethical representation of the client in dealing with authorities or other persons whose interests are adverse to the client.
